Looking at the structure of the problem, I need to show that the marginal distributions at coordinates `i` and `j` are equal when both are in `u`.

The key is:
1. Use composition of maps: `map (fun ω => i ∈ X ω) P = map (fun s => i ∈ s) (map X P)`
2. Apply `hX.map_eq` to get `map X P = Ber(u, p)`
3. Since `i, j ∈ u`, their marginals from the Bernoulli product are identical

```lean
lemma IsBernoulliOn.identDistrib_mem (hX : IsBernoulliOn X u p P) (hi : i ∈ u) (hj : j ∈ u) :
    IdentDistrib (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) (fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω) P P where
  aemeasurable_fst := by fun_prop
  aemeasurable_snd := by fun_prop
  map_eq := by
    have : ∀ k ∈ u, map (fun s : Set ι => k ∈ s) Ber(u, p) = 
      toNNReal p • dirac true + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac false := by
      intro k hk
      rw [bernoulliOn_eq_map, Measure.map_map measurable_setOf, Measure.infinitePi_map_pi]
      · simp [hk]
      · intro; exact measurable_mem
    simp only [← Measure.map_map measurable_mem hX.aemeasurable, hX.map_eq, this i hi, this j hj]
```
